<exercise checkit-seed="0004" checkit-slug="SQ3" checkit-title="Partial sum sequence">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    Consider the partial sum sequence <m>\displaystyle A_n=\left(-1\right)+\left(-\frac{3}{5}\right)+\left(-\frac{9}{25}\right)+\cdots+\left(-1\cdot \left( \frac{3}{5}\right)^n \right).</m>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Find a closed form for <m>A_n</m>.</li>
                        <li>Does <m>\{A_n\}</m> converge?  If so, to what value?</li>
                    </ol>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Consider the partial sum sequence <m>\displaystyle B_n=\sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{1}{2 \, {\left(i + 2\right)}}-\frac{1}{2 \, {\left(i + 3\right)}} \right).</m>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Find a closed form for <m>B_n</m>.</li>
                        <li>Does <m>\{B_n\}</m> converge?  If so, to what value?</li>
                    </ol>
                </li>
                
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle A_n=-1\cdot\frac{1-\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^{n+1} }{1- \left(\frac{3}{5}\right) }</m>.</li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\to\infty} -1\cdot\frac{1-\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^{n+1} }{1- \left(\frac{3}{5}\right) } </m> converges to <m>-\frac{5}{2}</m>.                
                        </li>            
                    </ol>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle B_n=\frac{1}{6}-\frac{1}{2 \, {\left(n + 3\right)}}</m>.</li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{1}{6}-\frac{1}{2 \, {\left(n + 3\right)}} </m> converges to <m>\frac{1}{6}</m>.                
                        </li>            
                    </ol>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </answer>
</exercise>
